Inferential Analysis for Egg Production

Author

Kiersten Gilberg, Kun Ya, Paolo De Lagrave-Codina

Published

December 8, 2023

Summary

This analysis aims to determine whether there is a difference in the mean number of eggs produced per hen between table eggs (i.e.Â unfertilized eggs for consumption) and hatching eggs (i.e.Â fertilized and will produce a chicken). The data used in this analysis was reported monthly from July 2016 to February of 2023 and was limited to the product type âallâ as this includes both conventionally housed and cage-free eggs produced in the United States of America. We conducted a 1000 sample permutation to test our null-hypothesis with an observed test statistic of 5.527 and a p-value of <0.001. Using a significance level of 0.05 we rejected the null hypothesis in favour of the alternative and concluded that there is a significant difference in the mean number of eggs produced per hen between table and hatching eggs.

Introduction

Eggs and poultry products continue to be a staple in the modern diet (Conrad et al. 2017). Although the proportion of the U.S. population consuming eggs remains steady, as the population grows the increase in demand for egg products requires larger yields from farmers (Conrad et al. 2017). Therefore, it is important for members of the egg industry to remain up to date on current egg yields, so that they can make informed economic decisions and continue to supply the population with egg products.

In this analysis we specifically look at the difference in table eggs and hatching eggs to answer the question: is there a difference in the mean number of eggs produced per hen between table and hatching eggs? Table eggs are unfertilized eggs that are used for consumption, whereas hatching eggs have been fertilized and will develop into chickens. Comparison of these two egg types can inform farmers on how to best approach their farming practices, as different egg types will require disparate processing strategies with individual costs and market prices (Stemberger 1959).

Methods

Data

The data used in this analysis was taken from the tidytuesday repository (Community 2023) and was originally sourced from Open Science Framework by Samara Mendez (Mendez 2023). Each row in the dataset represents summary data for the month, reporting on the type of egg (table vs hatching), the production process (conventional, cage-free, organic), the number of hens, the number of eggs, and the source of the data.

Analysis

The number of eggs per hen was calculated from the given data by dividing the total number of eggs produced in each category for the month by the number of hens. This gives a more accurate representation of how many eggs are produced for each group, since the total number of eggs will depend on the number of hens. We then calculated the observed test statistic, difference of the means, and generated a null distribution through a 1000 repetition permutation simulation. From this simulated null distribution we calculated the p-value for our observed test statistic. The R programming language (R Core Team 2023)] and the following packages were used to conduct the analysis: dplyr (Wickham et al. 2023), readr (Wickham, Hester, and Bryan 2023), infer (Couch et al. 2021) and ggplot2 (Wickham 2016).

We chose to use a permutation to test our null hypothesis for several reasons. Firstly, permutation tests offer a non-parametric alternative to traditional parametric tests such as t-tests. Unlike t-tests, permutation tests do not rely on specific distributional assumptions, making them suitable for various types of data. This flexibility is particularly advantageous when dealing with non-normally distributed or skewed data sets. In our case, since we did not know the underlying distribution we chose to use a permutation test. Secondly, permutation tests provide advantages over their parametric counterparts for small samples and populations (Berry, Johnston, and Mielke Jr 2011). They are highly adaptable and can be applied to a wide range of study designs. Our study had 80 examples for each condition (table vs.Â hatching eggs), but since we did not conduct a power analysis, the permutation test was the preferred method of analysis.

One assumption made in our analysis was the exchangeability of observations for the permutation test (Hayes 1996), meaning that any exchange of data points between groups is equally probable and independent. There were also several limitations of our analysis, our data was collected monthly but since we did include a time-series analysis we could not make any conclusions of how egg yields are changing. Additionally, the production processes for âcage-freeâ were only available for table eggs and not hatching eggs, this limited our analysis to only the âallâ process.

The data set provides insightful information across a range of variables, covering the period from July 2016 to March 2023. While this time frame offers a substantial amount of data, itâs worth noting that the relatively short range could potentially limit the depth of long-term trend analysis. The data set comprises six key variables:

Observed_month: As previously mentioned, this variable records the month and year of each data entry, offering a temporal context for the analysis.

Prod_type: This categorical variable classifies the type of egg production. It differentiates between âhatching eggsâ and âtable eggsâ, indicating whether the eggs are fertilized (hatching eggs) or not (table eggs). This distinction is crucial for understanding the purpose and method of production.

Prod_process: Another categorical variable, Prod_process, describes the method used in egg production. It categorizes production into specific types like âcage-freeâ, âorganicâ, and a comprehensive category labeled âallâ, which presumably encompasses various production methods.

N_hens: This numerical variable represents the number of hens, ranging significantly from 13,500,000 to 341,166,000. The presence of missing values in this variable should be noted, as they could impact the analysis.

N_eggs: Similarly numerical, this variable quantifies egg production, with values spanning from approximately 298 million to 8.6 billion. This wide range indicates a substantial variability in production output.

Source: This string variable identifies the data source for each row. Itâs unique to each entry and, given its nature, may not be directly relevant to the analysis of production trends but is crucial for data verification and traceability.

Overall, this data set offers a comprehensive overview of egg production, encompassing various aspects from production types to the number of hens involved, thereby facilitating a multifaceted analysis of the industry within the specified timeframe. We can also see that we have a relatively low number of rows: 320 this is in part related to the low time frame of the analysis and can also limit the reliability.

Histogram of the Number of Eggs per Month:

This histogram displays multiple peaks and a large gap between some peaks, indicating the data could be multimodal. There are distinct high-frequency counts at various intervals of egg production. These peaks suggest that there are several common levels of monthly egg production, which could reflect different production capacities, seasonal variations, or other factors that influence how many eggs are produced in a given month.

Histogram of the Number of Hens per Month:

Similarly, the number of hens per month also shows a possible multimodal distribution with several peaks. These counts might correspond to different sizes of farms that operate with different numbers of hens depending on their capacity.

Correlated Relationship: The similar shapes of the distributions suggest that the number of hens and the number of eggs produced each month are related in a predictable manner. Investigating this further could involve feature engineering by taking the average number of eggs produced per hen instead of looking at aggregated features which would allow us to normalize the data.

Distribution of Production Type:

The bar chart above shows a large difference in the count between the two categories of egg production type. Table eggs have a much higher count compared to hatching eggs in this data set. This can be seen as an unbalanced variable in our data, which could be problematic for analysis. It may be necessary to normalize this feature depending on the analysis.

Distribution of Production Process:

The âallâ category has the highest count compared to the two other cage-free processes. The âallâ category represents both cage-free and non-cage-free hens. The counts for âcage-free (non-organic)â and âcage-free (organic)â are relatively similar and notably less than the âallâ category. This suggests that both organic and non-organic cage-free productions are significant but still less than the âallâ category. This categorical variable, if used, should be approached with caution because the âallâ category includes data from the other categories, meaning the variables are interrelated.

Research Question and Hypotheses

We aimed to investigate whether there is a difference in the average number of eggs produced by each hen between hatching eggs and table eggs. To address this question, we formulated the following hypotheses:

Let \(\mu_{hatching}\) represent the population mean number of eggs produced by each hen for hatching, and \(\mu_{table}\) represent the population mean number of eggs produced by each hen for table eggs.

\(H_{0}\): The mean number of eggs produced by each hen for hatching, \(\mu_{hatching}\), is equal to the mean number of eggs produced by each hen for table eggs, \(\mu_{table}\). Mathematically, \(\mu_{hatching} = \mu_{table}\).

\(H_{A}\): The mean number of eggs produced by each hen for hatching, \(\mu_{hatching}\), is NOT equal to the mean number of eggs produced by each hen for table eggs, \(\mu_{table}\). Mathematically, \(\mu_{hatching} \ne \mu_{table}\).

Observed Test Statistic

To test these hypotheses, we calculated the observed test statistic \(\delta^{*}\), which represents the difference between the observed mean number of eggs produced by each hen for hatching eggs and the observed mean number of eggs produced by each hen for table eggs, as derived from our egg production data set.

The observed test statistic \(\delta^{*}\) = \(\hat{\mu}_\text{hatching} - \hat{\mu}_\text{table}\)

Hypothesis Test Using the Permutation Method

With these hypotheses and observed test statistic in place, we can conduct our hypothesis test using the permutation method to draw conclusions about the potential differences in egg yield between the two types.

In our data wrangling phase, we calculated the mean number of eggs produced per hen, recognizing that the total number of eggs depends on the number of hens involved.

Additionally, it is important to note that the âcage-freeâ production process is only applicable to table eggs, not hatching eggs. To ensure a fair and accurate comparison between hatching and table eggs, we filtered the data set to include only entries where the âprod_processâ variable was labeled as âallâ.

Subsequently, we calculated the observed test statistic, to assess the difference in egg yield between hatching and table eggs, with careful consideration of handling any missing values (NA).

With the test statistic in hand, as shown in TableÂ 5, we conducted our hypothesis test using the permutation method. We generated a null distribution through 1,000 permutations, simulating the expected outcome assuming there was no difference in egg yield between the two types.

TableÂ 6: P-value for Hypotheses Test
p-value 0

The p-value obtained from our hypothesis test, as shown in TableÂ 6, is <0.001, which is an extremely rare occurrence. Given that our defined significance threshold \(\alpha\) is 0.05, we can reject the null hypothesis \(H_{0}\)(there is no difference in the average number of eggs produced by each hen between hatching eggs and table eggs) in favor of the alternative hypothesis \(H_{A}\).

Please note the following from the infer documentation about p-values of zero:

Though a true p-value of 0 is impossible,Â get_p_value()Â may return 0 in some cases. This is due to the simulation-based nature of the {infer} package; the output of this function is an approximation based on the number ofÂ repsÂ chosen in theÂ generate()Â step. When the observed statistic is very unlikely given the null hypothesis, and only a small number ofÂ repsÂ have been generated to form a null distribution, it is possible that the observed statistic will be more extreme than every test statistic generated to form the null distribution, resulting in an approximate p-value of 0. In this case, the true p-value is a small value likely less thanÂ 3/repsÂ (based on a poisson approximation). (Couch et al. 2021)

Results Visualization

Weâve created a visualization FigureÂ 3 to further illustrate our earlier conclusion. The red vertical line on the plot represents our observed test statistic obtained from our data, which lies within the rejection region as marked by the blue dashed lines. It demonstrates that our observed test statistic would be highly unlikely to occur under the null hypothesis.

Limitations

While our findings align with our initial expectations, it is essential to recognize certain limitations inherent in our study design. Firstly, our study focused on a specific geographic region, the United States, and the results may not be directly applicable to other regions or countries. Secondly, our data granularity was limited to monthly data points from 2023 to 2026. This temporal granularity, although suitable for our analysis, may not capture finer variations in the data. Furthermore, since the data is recorded on a monthly basis as a time series, there may be underlying temporal patterns among observations from consecutive months.

Moving forward, it is important to consider more comprehensive analyses, such as time series modeling, to explore trends and patterns in the data over time. Additionally, expanding the study to include data from a broader range of geographic locations would enhance the generalizability of our findings.

Implications and Future Research Directions

In practical terms, this means that hatching eggs and table eggs do indeed exhibit distinct patterns of egg production by each hen. It suggests that tailoring production strategies for these two egg types may be necessary to optimize yields and meet consumer demands efficiently.

Looking ahead, our research paves the way for future investigations. One promising direction is to explore the effects of different production processes on table eggs through a regression analysis. Understanding how variations in processing methods are associated with table and hatching egg production could offer valuable insights for both the egg industry and consumers.
